'''''Saetta''''' was a {{sclass-|Folgore|cruiser|0}} [[torpedo cruiser]] built for the Italian ''[[Regia Marina]]'' (Royal Navy) in the 1880s. Armed with three {{convert|14|in|abbr=on|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s and six light guns, she was capable of a top speed of {{convert|17|kn|lk=in}}. She was built in the mid-1880s, was [[ship launching|launched]] in May 1887, and was [[ship commissioning|completed]] in February 1888. ''Saetta'' spent the first decade of her career serving in the main Italian fleet, where she conducted peacetime training exercises. In 1897, she was withdrawn from front-line service and employed as a gunnery [[training ship]], a role she filled for another decade. The ''Regia Marina'' ultimately sold ''Saetta'' for scrap in May 1908.

==Design==
{{main|Folgore-class cruiser}}

''Saetta'' was {{convert|56.7|m|sp=us}} [[length overall|long overall]] and had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|6.31|m|abbr=on}} and an average [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|2.15|m|abbr=on}}. She displaced {{convert|364|MT|sp=us}} normally. Her propulsion system consisted of a pair of horizontal [[compound engine|double-expansion]] [[steam engine]]s each driving a single [[screw propeller]], with steam supplied by four coal-fired [[locomotive boiler]]s. ''Saetta'' could steam at a speed of {{convert|17|kn|lk=in}} from {{convert|2130|ihp|lk=in}}. She had a crew of between 57&ndash;70.<ref name=G347>Gardiner, p. 347</ref>

The primary armament for ''Saetta'' was three {{convert|14|in|abbr=on|0}} [[torpedo tube]]s. She was also equipped with two {{convert|57|mm|abbr=on}} /43 guns and four {{convert|37|mm|abbr=on|1}} /25 guns, all mounted singly. The ship carried no armor protection.<ref name=G347/>

==Service history==
[[File:Italian cruiser Saetta.jpg|thumb|left|''Saetta'' in 1905]]

''Saetta'' was built at the [[Regio Cantiere di Castellammare di Stabia]] (Royal Dockyard in [[Castellammare di Stabia]]). She was launched on 30 May 1887, and was completed on 16 February 1888.<ref name=G347/> That year, she took part in the annual fleet maneuvers, along with five [[ironclad warship|ironclads]], a [[protected cruiser]], the torpedo cruisers {{ship|Italian cruiser|Tripoli||2}}, {{ship|Italian cruiser|Goito||2}}, and {{ship|Italian cruiser|Folgore||2}}, and numerous smaller vessels. The maneuvers consisted of close-order drills and a simulated attack on and defense of La Spezia. Later that year, the ship was present during a naval review held for the [[German Emperor|German Kaiser]] [[Wilhelm II]] during a visit to Italy.<ref>Brassey, p. 453</ref> In 1892, the ''Regia Marina'' used ''Saetta'' to conduct experiments with oil-fired boilers.<ref name=G347/>

In 1893, ''Saetta'' was [[:wikt:laid up|laid up]] in [[Naples]] for the year; at the time, the Italian fleet mobilized only a handful of vessels for the annual training maneuvers, preferring to keep the most modern vessels in reserve to reduce maintenance costs.<ref>"Naval and Military Notes &ndash; Italy" (1893), p. 567</ref> The following year, ''Saetta'' was commissioned for two months to take part in the annual fleet maneuvers; she spent the rest of the year in reserve.<ref>"Naval and Military Notes – Italy" (1894, no. 196), p. 565</ref> She took part in the annual fleet maneuvers in the Reserve Division, along with the ironclad {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}} and {{ship|Italian ironclad|Andrea Doria||2}} and the torpedo cruiser {{ship|Italian cruiser|Urania||2}}.<ref>"Naval and Military Notes &ndash; Italy" (1894, no. 197), p. 776</ref> ''Saetta'' was stationed in [[La Spezia]] in the 1st Maritime Department, along with her [[sister ship]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Folgore||2}} in 1895,<ref>"Naval and Military Notes – Italy" (1895), p. 90</ref> though the latter had been badly damaged in a collision and was decommissioned.<ref name=G347/> 

From 1897 to 1900, the ship served as a torpedo training ship. The following year, she was transferred to the gunnery school, where she train gunners for the fleet. In 1902, her gun armament was expanded to increase the types of weapons available for training.<ref name=G347/> These included one {{convert|3|in|abbr=on}} gun, four 57&nbsp;mm guns, two {{convert|47|mm|abbr=on}} guns, one 37&nbsp;mm gun, and one 37&nbsp;mm revolving [[Hotchkiss gun]].<ref>Gardiner & Gray, p. 257</ref> That year, the gunnery school also included the old ironclads {{ship|Italian ironclad|Regina Maria Pia||2}} and {{ship|Italian ironclad|Affondatore||2}}; ''Saetta'' was used only for target practice at sea.<ref>"Naval Notes &ndash; Italy", p. 1,075</ref> She was still serving in this capacity in 1904&ndash;05, along with the old [[ironclad warship|ironclad]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Enrico Dandolo||2}}.<ref>"Naval Notes – Italy", p. 1429</ref> ''Saetta'' was ultimately discarded on 14 May 1908 and subsequently [[ship breaking|broken up]] for scrap.<ref name=G347/>

